SKILL|songwriting-and-ai-music|"Songwriting craft and Suno AI music prompts."
STEP|1|Intro — set the mood, pull the listener in
STEP|2|Verse — the story, the details, the world-building
STEP|3|Pre-Chorus — optional tension ramp before the payoff
STEP|4|Chorus — the emotional core, the part people remember
STEP|5|Bridge — a detour, a shift in perspective or key
STEP|6|Outro — the farewell, can echo or subvert the rest
STEP|7|Perfect: lean/mean
STEP|8|Family: crate/braid
STEP|9|Assonance: had/glass (same vowels, different endings)
STEP|10|Consonance: scene/when (different vowels, similar endings)
STEP|11|Near/slant: enough to suggest connection without locking it down
STEP|12|Matching syllable counts between parallel lines helps singability
STEP|13|The STRESSED syllables matter more than total count
STEP|14|Say it out loud. If you stumble, the meter needs work.
STEP|15|Intentionally breaking meter can create emphasis or surprise
STEP|16|Whisper before a scream hits harder than just screaming
STEP|17|Sparse before dense. Slow before fast. Low before high.
STEP|18|The drop only works because of the buildup
STEP|19|Silence is an instrument
STEP|20|"I was sad" = flat
STEP|21|"Your hoodie's still on the hook by the door" = alive
STEP|22|But sometimes "I give my life" said plainly IS the power
STEP|23|The line people remember, hum, repeat
STEP|24|Usually the title or core phrase
STEP|25|Works best when melody + lyric + emotion all align
STEP|26|Place it where it lands hardest (often first/last line of chorus)
STEP|27|Stable feelings (resolution, peace) pair with settled melodies,
STEP|28|Unstable feelings (longing, doubt) pair with wandering melodies,
STEP|29|Verse melody typically sits lower, chorus goes higher
STEP|30|But flip this if it serves the song
STEP|31|Cliches on autopilot ("heart of gold" without earning it)
STEP|32|Forcing word order to hit a rhyme ("Yoda-speak")
STEP|33|Same energy in every section (flat dynamics)
STEP|34|Treating your first draft as sacred — revision is creation
STEP|35|Count syllables per line
STEP|36|Mark the rhyme scheme (ABAB, AABB, etc.)
STEP|37|Identify which syllables are STRESSED
STEP|38|Note where held/sustained notes fall
STEP|39|Match stressed syllables to the same beats as the original
STEP|40|Total syllable count can flex by 1-2 unstressed syllables
STEP|41|On long held notes, try to match the VOWEL SOUND of the original
STEP|42|Monosyllabic swaps in key spots keep rhythm intact
STEP|43|Sing your new words over the original — if you stumble, revise
STEP|44|Pick a concept strong enough to sustain the whole song
STEP|45|Start from the title/hook and build outward
STEP|46|Generate lots of raw material (puns, phrases, images) FIRST,
STEP|47|If you need a specific line somewhere, reverse-engineer the
STEP|48|V4.5+ supports up to 1,000 chars in Style field — use them
STEP|49|NO artist names or trademarks. Describe the sound instead.
STEP|50|Specify BPM and key when you have a preference
STEP|51|Use Exclude Styles field for what you DON'T want
STEP|52|Unexpected genre combos can be gold: "bossa nova trap",
STEP|53|Build a vocal PERSONA, not just a gender:
STEP|54|Always use Custom Mode for serious work (separate Style + Lyrics)
STEP|55|Lyrics field limit: ~3,000 chars (~40-60 lines)
STEP|56|Always add structural tags — without them Suno defaults to
STEP|57|Spell words as they SOUND: "through" -> "thru"
STEP|58|Proper nouns are highest failure rate — test early
STEP|59|"Nous" -> "Noose" (forces correct pronunciation)
STEP|60|Hyphenate to guide syllables: "Re-search", "bio-engineering"
STEP|61|ALL CAPS = louder, more intense
STEP|62|Vowel extension: "lo-o-o-ove" = sustained/melisma
STEP|63|Ellipses: "I... need... you" = dramatic pauses
STEP|64|Hyphenated stretch: "ne-e-ed" = emotional stretch
STEP|65|Spell out numbers: "24/7" -> "twenty four seven"
STEP|66|Space acronyms: "AI" -> "A I" or "A-I"
STEP|67|Test proper nouns/unusual words in a short 30-second clip first
STEP|68|Once generated, pronunciation is baked in — fix in lyrics BEFORE
STEP|69|Write the concept/hook first — what's the emotional core?
STEP|70|If adapting, map the original structure (syllables, rhyme, stress)
STEP|71|Generate raw material — brainstorm freely before structuring
STEP|72|Draft lyrics into the structure
STEP|73|Read/sing aloud — catch stumbles, fix meter
STEP|74|Build the Suno style description — paint the dynamic journey
STEP|75|Add metatags to lyrics for performance direction
STEP|76|Generate 3-5 variations minimum — treat them like recording takes
STEP|77|Pick the best, use Extend/Continue to build on promising sections
STEP|78|If something great happens by accident, keep it
STEP|79|Describing the dynamic ARC in the style field matters way more
STEP|80|Keeping some original lines intact in a parody adds recognizability
STEP|81|The bridge slot in a song is where you can transform imagery.
STEP|82|Monosyllabic word swaps in hooks/tags are the cleanest way to
STEP|83|A strong vocal persona description in the style field makes a
STEP|84|Don't be precious about rules. If a line breaks meter but hits
